column13: setup: Do not try to generate seahub db when it exists
column20:
When using setup-seafile-mysql.sh it asks you if you want to use an
existing database or create a new one. Even when you choose the 'Use
existing' option, it tries to create the seahub DB, and then the
installer fails because it tries to create already existing tables.
Fix is to remember the answer to the previous choice and only create the
seahub DB if you are creating a new DB.

But there is a case, where you don't have permission to create dbs, but instead you get provisioned, empty databases and only have write permissions inside them.
So it is valid to create all tables even when using an "existing" database.
I don't think this behaviour should be changed. But you could add another (third) option for your case.

column13: [install-scripts] customize url/branch of projects via envars
column20:
When building seafile it fetches its dependencies from a hardcoded
github url. This commit permit running the integration tests and
building the final installer package using seahub (for example) from
another repo/branch than the default one by defining the environment
variable PROJECT_SEAFILE_URL and PROJECT_SEAFILE_BRANCH to point to a
git repo and branch reference, respectively.

column21:
Also, if you want to clone all repos from your own fork, instead of specifying all envars (PROJECT_SEAHUB_URL, PROJECT_LIBSEARPC_URL, ...) you can specify PROJECT_ALL_BASE_URL to point to https://github.com/youruser and it will clone them from https://github.com/youruser/seahub, https://github.com/youruser/libsearpc, and so on...).
Similar with branches, if you need to clone the branch foobar of all branches, specify the PROJECT_ALL_BRANCH envar.
Great! :-)

column21:
I have some ideas about package organization. I think only 5 packages are necessary:

seafile-daemon: built from haiwen/seafile project. It contains the syncing engine and libseafile library. There is no need to built a separate libseafile and libseafile-dev package. The dev headers is of no use since I can't think of any third-party will be interested in it. We can add it when there is such requirements later.
ccnet: built from haiwen/ccnet project. It contains the ccnet daemon and libccnet library. The current naming of libccnet is confusing. I suggest we change it to ccnet. It's a daemon, not a library.
seafile-gui: built from haiwen/seafile-client project. Actually seafile-gui is a more proper name for the project.
libsearpc: bulit from haiwen/libsearpc project.
seafile-client: a meta-package to install the above 4 packages.

Additionally we also provides a seafile-cli package.

column21:
thanks for sharing your ideas! you're right, the executables in libccnet need to get into a ccnet package, and adding a seafile-daemon package makes a lot of sense, as does naming the whole thing seafile-client. in effect, however, this will split things up in even more packages -- allthough that shouldn't be a problem.
for instance, libccnet contains the shared libraries that are linked with seafile-applet, so there should remain the libccnet package (and ccnet and seafile-gui will depend on it).
at first i thought that naming the meta-package different from the large official binary was a problem. but this could even be an improvement, as i can add "Conflicts: seafile" to the control file to make replacing one with the other much cleaner.
i've noticed i'll also need to rename the library packages to reflect their SONAME, and add a *.symbols file to them. i'll let you know when i'm ready.

column21:
i've restructured the packaging:

libsearpc1 (shared libraries)

libsearpc-dev (development files to build with shared libs)


ccnet (ccnet executables)

libccnet0 (shared libraries)
libccnet-dev (development files to build with shared libs)


seafile-daemon (the seafile daemon)

libseafile0 (shared libraries)
libseafile-dev (development files to build with shared libs)
seafile-cli (comand line interface)


seafile-gui (seafile desktop client)

i did not add another package called seafile-client because i noticed that seafile-gui does already fulfill the task. i.e., if you install seafile-gui, all necessary dependencies (including libsearpc1, ccnet and seafile-daemon) will be installed as well.
also, i did not yet add symbols files to the library packages. but what do you think so far?
i've set up a new, clean PPA with this packaging scheme, you can try/examine it here:

https://launchpad.net/~m.eik/+archive/ubuntu/seafile

last but not least, here's an updated script that temporarily clones the four github repos i forked and prepares ready-to-build debian source packages in the specified directory:

http://reaktanz.de/stuff/oathaiqu/deb_git_seafile.sh

i used that in conjunction with backportpackage (from package ubuntu-dev-tools) to upload the package sources to the PPA.

i've now added initial symbols files to packages with shared libraries, and fixed various issues lintian was complaining about. the packages are in pretty good shape already.
the remaining issues include an error regarding the installation target of the pkg-config files i don't fully grasp yet (regarding /usr/lib/pkg-config and multiarch packages), missing documentation/manpages for several executables (which unfortunately i can't write), and complaints about python scripts that are installed to /usr/bin having the *.py extension. those should be renamed (no extension) if possible, to comply with debian packaging standards.

it can be used for proper packaging, building three binary packages:

Add support for PKG_CONFIG_PATH/PKG_CONFIG_LIBDIR env vars for libcrypto and libssl
column20:
This enables support for compiling seafile using an OpenSSL version installed outside the system's default prefix. Until seafile supports openssl 1.1.0, this is required to compile for example on Archlinux where the current openssl 1.0.2 package will soon be upgraded to 1.1.0, and the future 1.0.2 package's files will go into /usr/lib/openssl-1.0.
To use this, execute export PKG_CONFIG_PATH=/usr/lib/openssl-1.0/lib/pkgconfig prior to running autogen.sh.

column21: 2fa should be an optional argument. The code should handle the case where 2fa argument is given. Can you update the code?

column13: Add support to two-factor authentication to seaf-cli
column21:
Yes, the 2fa is an optional argument.
Function add_argument() will treat the argument as optional if the "required" parameter is not explicitly set to True.
https://docs.python.org/2/library/argparse.html#required
If the user doesn't have the 2FA-enabled, he can simply omit the -a (or --tfa) argument.
I test it using accounts with/without 2FA enabled. Both cases can work.

column13: seaf-cli support for reading password from file

column20:
Glib release 2.67.3 started conditionally using some C++ code[1] in the
public headers and it's no longer legal to include "glib.h" or anything
that includes it transitively from extern "C" block.
The solution recommended by the glib developers is to enclose all
declarations in a header within G_BEGIN_DECLS and G_END_DECLS as shown
in gobject developer manual[2]. Since G_BEGIN/END_DECLS expands to an
extern "C" block it's also acceptable to use it directly when "glib.h"
is not included in the current header file.
[1] https://gitlab.gnome.org/GNOME/glib/-/merge_requests/1715
[2] https://developer.gnome.org/gobject/stable/howto-gobject.html#howto-gobject-header
